# Troubleshooting Jenkins on EC2 (Terminal Only)

This document covers common Jenkins and EC2 issues and their fixes using terminal commands only.

Jenkins service not running:
Check status:
sudo systemctl status jenkins
Start Jenkins:
sudo systemctl start jenkins
Restart Jenkins:
sudo systemctl restart jenkins
Enable Jenkins on reboot:
sudo systemctl enable jenkins

Jenkins not opening on port 8080:
Check if Jenkins is listening on port 8080:
sudo netstat -tulnp | grep 8080
OR
sudo ss -tulnp | grep 8080
If no output appears, Jenkins is not running properly.

Java not found or Jenkins fails to start:
Check Java version:
java -version
Install Java on Amazon Linux:
sudo yum install java-11-amazon-corretto -y
Install Java on Ubuntu:
sudo apt update
sudo apt install openjdk-11-jdk -y
Verify Java installation:
java -version

SSH permission denied or connection issue:
Check current user:
whoami
Correct usernames:
Amazon Linux -> ec2-user
Ubuntu -> ubuntu
Fix key file permission on local machine:
chmod 400 jenkins-key.pem

Jenkins service fails to start:
Check Jenkins logs:
sudo journalctl -u jenkins --no-pager
Check live logs:
sudo journalctl -u jenkins -f

Permission denied errors inside Jenkins:
Check file permissions:
ls -l
Fix execute permission:
chmod +x filename.sh
Fix Jenkins directory ownership:
sudo chown -R jenkins:jenkins /var/lib/jenkins

Disk or memory issue:
Check disk usage:
df -h
Check memory usage:
free -h

Jenkins not starting after reboot:
Start Jenkins manually:
sudo systemctl start jenkins
Enable Jenkins at boot:
sudo systemctl enable jenkins

Most commonly used troubleshooting commands:
sudo systemctl status jenkins
sudo systemctl start jenkins
sudo systemctl restart jenkins
sudo journalctl -u jenkins
java -version
df -h

